Find the Lowest-Forecast-RMSE Model in First Differences


Since the professor asks us to estimate in first differences, I’m comparing many models in first differences.

1. Analyze the Frist 80% Training Set of Each Series’ First Difference

Employment 1st Diff Training Set passes the ADF test under a 5% critical value, but not the Ljung-Box test up to 24 lags. The correlogram suggests an AR(3) effect.

CPI 1st Diff Training Set doesn’t passes the ADF test under a 5% critical value, nor the Ljung-Box test up to 24 lags. The correlogram suggests an AR(1) or AR(3) effect.

IPI 1st Diff Training Set passes the ADF test under a 5% critical value, but not the Ljung-Box test up to 24 lags. The correlogram suggests little ARMA effects.

Treasury 1st Diff Training Set passes the ADF test under a 5% critical value, but not the Ljung-Box test up to 24 lags. The correlogram suggests little ARMA effect.

3. Forecast the Best Model

Employment 1st Diff and Inflation 1st Diff as endogenous variables, IPI 1st Diff as exogenous variable, no constant, no season, lag=8.

4. Analyze the Forecast Error of the Best Model

Employment 1st Diff forecast error passes the ADF test up to 24 lags and passes the Ljung-Box test up to 10 lags when critical value=5%. The correlogram suggests no ARMA effect.

CPI 1st Diff forecast error passes the ADF test up to 24 lags but not the Ljung-Box test up to 24 lags when critical value=5%. The correlogram suggests no ARMA effect.


Next, I can convert the first-differneces back to levels, and compare the performances in levels.
